04418nam a22006735i 9781477301593DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211990txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814773015937 a10.7560/7763192doi  a(DE-B1597)587433  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPS430b.P35 1990 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.72201 aPalmeri, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSatire in Narrative :bPetronius, Swift, Gibbon, Melville, & Pynchon /cFrank Palmeri. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (195 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Satiric Parody of Classicism in the Satyricon -- t2. Satiric Materialism in A Tale of a Tub -- t3. Satire, Epic, and History in The Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire -- t4. The Dialogue of Credit and Doubt in The Confidence-Man: His Masquerade -- t5. Parody and Paradigms in The Crying of Lot 49 -- tEpilogue: Borges, Satire, and History -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVirtually all theories of satire define it as a criticism of contemporary society. Some argue that satire criticizes the present in favor of a standard of values that has been superseded, and thus that satire is generally backward-looking and conservative. While this is often true of poetic satire, in this study Frank Palmeri asserts that narrative satire performs a different function, that it parodies both the established view of the world and that of its opponents, offering its own distinctive critical perspective. This theory of satire builds on the idea of dialogical parody in the work of Russian theorist Mikhail Bakhtin, while revising Bakhtin's estimate of carnival. In Palmeri's view, the carnivalesque offers only an inverted mirror image of authoritative discourse, while parodic narrative satire suggests an alternative to both the official world and its inverted opposite. Palmeri applies this theory of narrative satire to five works of world literature, each of which has generated sharp controversy about the genre to which it rightly belongs: Petronius' Satyricon, Jonathan Swift's A Tale of a Tub, Edward Gibbon's Decline and Fall of the Roman Empire, Herman Melville's The Confidence-Man, and Thomas Pynchon's The Crying of Lot 49. He analyzes the features that link these works and shows how the changing pairs of alternatives that are parodied in these satires reflect changes in the terms of social and cultural oppositions. Satire in Narrative will appeal to comparatists, specialists in eighteenth-century and American literature, and others interested in theories of genre and the relations between literary forms and social history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric)xHistory. 0aSatirexRoman influences. 0aSatire, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aSatire, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aSatire, LatinxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/77631940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477301593423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477301593/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK